You can write a try-catch block that catches all unhandled exceptions and restarts the application by calling its own executable file. Here's an example:

```
using System;
using System.Diagnostics; // Required for restarting the application

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        while (true) // Keep repeating the program loop
        {
            try
            {
                // Your application code goes here...
                // For example:
                Console.Write("Enter a number: ");
                int num = int.Parse(Console.ReadLine());
                Console.WriteLine("You entered: " + num);
            }
            catch (Exception ex)
            {
                Console.WriteLine("An error occurred: " + ex.Message);

                // Restart the application by calling its own executable file
                string filename = Process.GetCurrentProcess().MainModule.FileName;
                Process.Start(filename);
                Environment.Exit(0); // Exit the current instance of the application
            }
        }
    }
}
```

This code uses an infinite loop (`while (true)`) to keep the program running. Inside the loop, an example piece of code is included that reads an integer from the console and writes it back out. This can be replaced with your own code.

The `try` block contains the code that should run normally. If an exception occurs, the `catch` block will execute. This block writes an error message to the console and then restarts the application by calling its own executable file using the `Process.Start` method.

After calling `Process.Start`, the current instance of the application calls `Environment.Exit(0)` to exit gracefully, allowing the new instance to take over. Without this line, multiple instances of the application would continue running simultaneously.

You can use the `Thread.Sleep` method to wait for a specified number of milliseconds between each iteration of the loop. Here's an example:

```
