You can adjust the `5000` value to whatever number of milliseconds you want to wait between each iteration.

If you want to run a `foreach` loop for every item in a list simultaneously, you can use the `Parallel.ForEach` method from the `System.Threading.Tasks` namespace. This method partitions the input collection into multiple parts and processes each part on a separate thread, which allows the loop to execute in parallel.

Here's an example that demonstrates how to use `Parallel.ForEach`:

```
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        List<string> names = new List<string> { "John", "Mary", "Bob", "Alice" };

        Parallel.ForEach(names, name =>
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Processing " + name);

            // Your processing code goes here...
            // For example:
            for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++)
            {
                Console.WriteLine("  " + name + " - task " + i);
            }
        });

        Console.WriteLine("Done processing all names.");
    }
}
```

This code defines a `List<string>` containing some names. It then calls `Parallel.ForEach(names, name => { ... })` to process each name in the list in parallel.

The lambda expression `name => { ... }` represents the code to execute for each item in the list. In this example, it prints a message indicating which name is being processed, then runs a simple `for` loop to simulate some processing tasks.

Note that the order in which the iterations are processed is not necessarily the same as the order in the original list. Also, because the loop is executing in parallel, there is no guarantee that all iterations will complete in the same order on each run of the program.

